Jenkins Deployment Using Docker
🎯 Objective

To run Jenkins inside Docker using Docker Compose, create a Pipeline job, generate a simple static Karunya University website, publish it inside Jenkins using the HTML Publisher plugin, and archive the generated files as build artifacts.

✅ Step 1 — Open Docker Desktop
Open Docker Desktop
Wait until Docker is fully running
Check

Run:

docker --version
✅ Step 2 — Open Command Prompt
Press Win + R
Type:
cmd
Press Enter
✅ Step 3 — Create the project folder

Copy and paste:

mkdir jenkins-static-site
cd jenkins-static-site
What this does

Creates a folder named jenkins-static-site and moves into it.

✅ Step 4 — Create docker-compose.yml

Copy and paste:

notepad docker-compose.yml

If Notepad asks to create a new file, click Yes.

Paste this:

version: '3.8'

services:
  jenkins:
    image: jenkins/jenkins:lts
    container_name: jenkins
    restart: unless-stopped
    ports:
      - "8080:8080"
      - "50000:50000"
    volumes:
      - jenkins_home:/var/jenkins_home
      - /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock

volumes:
  jenkins_home:
    driver: local
Save correctly
Click File → Save As
File name:
docker-compose.yml
Save as type:
All Files (*.*)
Click Save
Close Notepad
Check

Run:

dir

You should see docker-compose.yml

✅ Step 5 — Start Jenkins container

Copy and paste:

docker compose up -d
What this does

Starts Jenkins in the background using Docker Compose.

Check

Run:

docker ps

You should see a container named jenkins

✅ Step 6 — Get the Jenkins initial password

Copy and paste:

docker exec jenkins cat /var/jenkins_home/secrets/initialAdminPassword
What this does

Displays the initial admin password required for first-time Jenkins setup.

Check

A long password string will be shown in the terminal.

✅ Step 7 — Open Jenkins in browser

Open:

http://localhost:8080
Do this
Paste the password from terminal
Click Continue
Click Install suggested plugins
Create your admin username and password
Finish setup
Check

Jenkins dashboard should open successfully.

✅ Step 8 — Install HTML Publisher plugin

From Jenkins dashboard:

Click the gear icon at the top right
This opens Manage Jenkins
Click Plugins
Open Available Plugins
In the search box type:
HTML Publisher
Tick the checkbox
Click:
Install without restart
Why this is needed

The pipeline uses publishHTML, so without this plugin the build fails.

Check

Plugin installation should complete successfully.

✅ Step 9 — Create a Pipeline job

From Jenkins dashboard:

Click New Item
In item name type:
karunya-site-pipeline
Select:
Pipeline
Click OK
Check

Pipeline configuration page opens.

✅ Step 10 — Add Pipeline script

Scroll down to the Pipeline section.

Set:

Definition = Pipeline script

Paste this script:

pipeline {
    agent any

    stages {
        stage('Generate site') {
            steps {
                script {
                    sh 'rm -rf site || true'
                    sh 'mkdir -p site/assets'

                    writeFile file: 'site/index.html', text: """
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="utf-8"/>
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1"/>
<title>Karunya University — Simple Site</title>
<link rel="stylesheet" href="assets/style.css"/>
</head>
<body>
<header class="site-header">
<div class="container">
<h1>Karunya University</h1>
<p class="tagline">Values — Knowledge — Service</p>
</div>
</header>
<main class="container">
<section class="card">
<h2>About Karunya University</h2>
<p>Karunya Institute of Technology and Sciences is a leading centre for higher education in India.</p>
</section>
</main>
<footer class="site-footer container">
<p>&copy; ${new Date().format('yyyy')} Karunya University — Generated by Jenkins</p>
</footer>
</body>
</html>
"""

                    writeFile file: 'site/assets/style.css', text: """
body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; margin:0; }
.container { max-width:800px; margin:0 auto; padding:20px; }
.site-header { background:#0b3d91; color:#fff; padding:20px; }
.tagline { font-size:14px; opacity:0.8; }
.card { background:#fff; border:1px solid #ddd; padding:15px; margin:15px 0; border-radius:6px; }
.site-footer { text-align:center; font-size:12px; color:#555; margin-top:20px; }
"""
                }
            }
        }

        stage('Publish site') {
            steps {
                publishHTML([
                    allowMissing: false,
                    alwaysLinkToLastBuild: true,
                    keepAll: true,
                    reportDir: 'site',
                    reportFiles: 'index.html',
                    reportName: 'Karunya University - Simple Site'
                ])
            }
        }
    }

    post {
        always {
            archiveArtifacts artifacts: 'site/**', fingerprint: true
        }
    }
}

Then click Save

What this pipeline does
Deletes old site if present
Creates site and site/assets folders
Generates index.html
Generates style.css
Publishes the HTML page in Jenkins
Archives the site files as artifacts
✅ Step 11 — Run the pipeline

Open the job page.

Click:

Build Now
Check

A build number such as #1 or #2 will appear.

✅ Step 12 — View build result

Click the build number.

Then open:

Console Output
Check

The stages should run successfully.

If the plugin was missing earlier, build may fail at publishHTML. After installing the plugin and building again, it should succeed.

✅ Step 13 — View the published website

After successful build, on the left side of the build page you will see:

Karunya University - Simple Site

Click it.

Expected output

A webpage will open inside Jenkins showing:

Karunya University
Values — Knowledge — Service
About section
Footer generated by Jenkins
